<figureCitation box="[490,568,1272,1298]" captionStart="Figure 72" captionStartId="57.[192,268,1867,1893]" captionTargetBox="[192,1440,213,1828]" captionTargetId="figure-10@57.[192,1440,213,1828]" captionTargetPageId="57" captionText="Figure 72. Distribution map for Axina species: A. analis, A. conspicua, A. equestris, A. ingnota, A. ordinis, A. trinalis, A. fortipes, A. furcula, A. megaspina, A. sexmaculata." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4565005" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4565005/files/figure.png" pageId="37" pageNumber="36">Fig. 72</figureCitation>
). This species is known from 
<collectingCountry box="[897,965,1272,1298]" name="Brazil" pageId="37" pageNumber="36">Brazil</collectingCountry>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="37" pageNumber="36" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="37.[192,1440,1314,1374]" pageId="37" pageNumber="36">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[192,324,1314,1340]" pageId="37" pageNumber="36">Etymology.</emphasis>
The specific epithet, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Opitz" authorityYear="2020" box="[558,633,1314,1340]" class="Insecta" family="Cleridae" genus="Axina" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="37" pageNumber="36" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="ordinis">
<emphasis box="[558,633,1314,1340]" italics="true" pageId="37" pageNumber="36">ordinis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, is a Latin name with a meaning of “line”. I refer to the narrow black line at the base of the pronotum disc.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
